{"key":"processedPost-8843736","value":{"id":8843736,"first":8842365,"last":8843736,"when":1219974750,"utime":"08/29/08 04:52 AM","content":"Actually, I use antibiotic agar for germinating spores too.&nbsp; It gives you a head start on any bacteria that might be on your print.&nbsp; Once you have a clean culture, you transfer it to non-antibiotic treated grains and bulk substrates to grow anyway, so it's only in the spore stage for that use.<br /><br />It's also quite valuable for cloning wild mushrooms.&nbsp; There's so much live bacteria in wild mushrooms that even with antibiotic agar, you'll still need to make a series of transfers until you have a clean culture, but it will help somewhat.&nbsp; I've never experienced any reasons not to use it and lots of reasons to.<br />RR","title":"Re: Disadvantages to Antibiotic Malt Extract Agar???","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}